The people of Macedonia decided in a referendum on Sunday whether to change their name to "Republic of North Macedonia", a move that would resolve a decades-long conflict with Greece, which had blocked its bid for membership in the European Union and NATO.
Greece, which has a province called Macedonia, maintains that the name of its northern neighbor is a claim to its territory and has vetoed its entry into NATO and the EU.
In June, both governments reached an agreement on the proposed new name, but nationalist opponents argue that the change would undermine the ethnic identity of the Slavic population, which is majority in Macedonia.
President Gjorge Ivanov has said he will not vote in the referendum and a boycott campaign has cast doubt on whether turnout will reach the minimum 50% required for the referendum to be considered valid.
The referendum ballot asked: "Are you in favour of joining NATO and the EU by accepting the agreement with Greece?"
Supporters of the name change, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, argue that it is a price worth paying for Macedonia, one of the countries emerging from the disintegration of Yugoslavia, to try to join bodies such as the EU and NATO.
"I came here today to vote for the future of the country, for the youth of Macedonia, so that they can live freely under the protection of the European Union, because this means a safer life for everyone", said Olivera Georgijevska, 79, in Skopje.
Although it will not be legally binding, enough Members of Parliament have said they will respect the result of the vote to make it decisive.
The name change requires a two-thirds majority in Parliament.
The State Election Commission stated that, as of 1 p.m., no irregularities had been reported.
However, turnout was only 16%, compared to 34% in the last parliamentary elections held in 2016, when 66% of registered voters cast their ballots.
'I came to vote for my children, our place is in Europe', said Gjose Tanevski, 62, who was voting in the capital, Skopje.
Zoran Zaev, Prime Minister of Macedonia, his wife Zorica and son Dushko cast their votes in Macedonia's referendum on a name change that would open the way to joining NATO and the European Union in Strumica, Macedonia on September 30, 2018.
In front of the Parliament in Skopje, 54-year-old Vladimir Kavardarkov was preparing a small stage and removing chairs in front of the tents planted by those who were going to boycott the referendum.
'We are in favour of joining NATO and the EU, but we want to do it with our heads held high, not through the back door,' said Kavadarkov.
We are a poor country, but we have dignity.
