The sea belongs to us: a landlocked Bolivia hopes the court will reopen the route to the Pacific
Sailors are guarding a naval headquarters in La Paz.
In public buildings, blue flags are waving.
From Lake Titicaca to the Amazon, naval bases display the motto: "The sea is ours by right,
To get it back is a duty.
Across Bolivia, a land without a sea, people still vividly remember the coast lost to Chile in a bloody conflict over resources in the 19th century, as well as the longing to sail the Pacific Ocean again.
These hopes may be the highest in decades, as Bolivia expects a resolution from the International Court of Justice by October 1, after five years of deliberations.
Bolivia has the momentum, a spirit of unity and serenity and, of course, is waiting for the result with a positive vision, commented Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will watch the International Court of Justice ruling on large screens across the country, hoping that the Hague court will rule in favor of Bolivia's claim that, after decades of intermittent talks, Chile has an obligation to negotiate to grant Bolivia a sovereign outlet to the sea.
Evo Morales, Bolivia's charismatic indigenous president, who is fighting a controversial battle for reelection next year, also has much to say about Monday's resolution.
"We are very close to returning to the Pacific Ocean", he promised by the end of August.
However, some analysts believe that the court is unlikely to rule in favor of Bolivia and that the situation would change little if it did.
The Netherlands-based UN body has no power to award Chilean territory and has stipulated that it will not determine the outcome of any talks.
The fact that the International Court of Justice's decision comes only six months after the final allegations indicates that the case was not complicated, said Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert in international law.
Far from advancing Bolivia's cause, the last four years may have stifled it.
The problem of access to the sea has been hijacked by the current Bolivian administration, said Zárate.
Furthermore, he suggested that Morales' belligerent rhetoric has undermined any residual Chilean goodwill.
Bolivia and Chile will continue to talk at some point, but it will be extremely difficult to hold talks after this.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Former president Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, Bolivia's representative in The Hague, rejected the idea that the court's decision-making process be unusually quick.
Monday will offer Bolivia "an extraordinary opportunity to open a new era of relations with Chile" and the possibility of "ending 139 years of disagreements with mutual benefits", he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales, who is still one of the most popular presidents in Latin America, used the maritime issue as a political crutch.
Bolivia will never give up its right to have access to the Pacific Ocean, he added.
Resolution is an opportunity to see that we have to leave the past behind
