John Edward: Language skills are fundamental for global citizens
Scotland's independent schools have a track record of academic excellence that has continued in 2018 with another set of extraordinary test scores that is reinforced by individual and collective successes in sports, the arts, music and other community projects.
With over 30 000 pupils across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to deliver the highest standard of service to pupils and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their pupils for further higher education, for their chosen career and for their place as world citizens.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a tailored curriculum, it is observed that modern languages remain a popular and desired subject in schools.
As Nelson Mandela said, "If you talk to a man in a language he understands, it goes to his head".
If you speak to him in his language, it goes to his heart.
This is a powerful reminder that if you want to build relationships and build trust with people from other countries, you cannot rely on English alone.
If we take into account the recent results of this year's examinations, we can see that languages are at the top of the ranking tables, with the highest pass rates in the independent schools.
In total, 68% of pupils who studied foreign languages obtained an A, the highest grade.
The data, collected from the 74 centres that are part of SCIS, showed that 72% of students were getting an A in Mandarin, while 72% of those studying German, 69% of those studying French and 63% of those studying Spanish were also getting an A.
This shows that the independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as a key skill that both children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Today, languages are considered to be on a par with STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curricula of independent schools everywhere.
A survey carried out in 2014 by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills revealed that of the reasons given by employers for the difficulties they encountered in filling jobs, 17% were attributed to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly indispensable in preparing young people for their future careers.
Potential job opportunities requiring languages are increasing, so these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of the career that someone chooses, if they have learned a second language, they will have a real advantage in the future thanks to a competition like this, which will last a lifetime.
The fact that he can communicate directly with people from foreign countries will allow him to automatically get ahead of the competition.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of over 4,000 UK adults, 75% of them did not speak any foreign language well enough to hold a conversation, and the only language spoken by a double-digit percentage, 15%, was French.
For this reason, investing in language education now is important for today's children.
If they know several languages, especially those of developing economies, children will be equipped to have better chances of finding quality employment.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
Some centres will focus on the more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages considered most important for the UK in the run-up to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the interests of a child, in independent schools he or she can always choose from a number of languages taught by specialist teachers.
Independent schools in Scotland are dedicated to providing a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills they need to succeed, whatever the future holds.
At this time, it is undeniable that in a global business environment, languages continue to be of vital importance for the future of the country, so this should be reflected in education.
Modern languages should be considered as 'competences for international communication'.
Independent schools will continue to offer these choices, diversity and excellence to the young people of Scotland.
It must be done well.
John Edward is the director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
