North Korea says there is "no chance" they will disarm first unilaterally if they don't have confidence
On Saturday, North Korea's foreign minister informed the United Nations that the continuation of sanctions deepened his distrust of the United States and that there was no possibility of his country unilaterally giving up nuclear weapons under such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual General Assembly of the international body that North Korea had taken "important goodwill measures" over the past year, such as stopping nuclear and missile tests, dismantling nuclear test facilities and committing to non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and technology.
However, we did not receive any similar response from the United States, he said.
If we don't have confidence in the United States, we can't have confidence in our national security, and, under those circumstances, there is no chance that we will disarm unilaterally first.
Although Ri repeated North Korea's well-known complaints about Washington's resistance to a "phased" denuclearization formula that rewards the country as it takes incremental steps, his statement is important, as he did not simply reject unilateral denuclearization, as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump following the first summit between a sitting US president and a North Korean leader on June 12 in Singapore, when Kim pledged to work towards the "denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula" and Trump guaranteed North Korea's security.
North Korea has pursued the official end of the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said Pyongyang must give up its nuclear weapons first.
Washington has also resisted calls to ease international sanctions on North Korea.
The US has insisted on denuclearization first and increased pressure through sanctions in order to achieve its purpose in a coercive manner, even objecting to a declaration of ending the war, Ri said.
The idea that sanctions can bring us to our knees is a chimera of people who don't know us.
The problem is that the continuation of sanctions deepens our mistrust.
Ri made no mention of plans for a second Kim-Trump summit, announced with much fanfare by the US leader to the United Nations earlier in the week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae in the past five months, adding: If South Korea had been the interested party in denuclearization instead of the United States, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have been in such a stalemate.
Even so, Ri's tone of speech was radically different from last year's speech, when he told the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable to direct North Korea's missiles towards US soil after the 'evil president' Trump, on a suicide mission, called Kim 'rocket man'.
At the United Nations this year, Trump, who last year threatened to "totally destroy" North Korea, praised Kim for his courageous move toward disarmament, but said much more needed to be done and sanctions needed to be maintained until North Korea denuclearized.
On Wednesday, Trump claimed there was no set deadline for this: "We can take two years, three years or five months, it doesn't matter".
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its advances.
However, as US Secretary of State Mike Pompeo informed the UN Security Council on Thursday: The imposition of Security Council sanctions must continue vigorously and without default until we make final and fully verified denuclearization a reality.
The Security Council has unanimously imposed sanctions on North Korea since 2006, in an attempt to cut off funding for Pyongyang's ballistic missile and nuclear programs.
Pompeo spoke with Ri outside the UN General Assembly and later commented that he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times this year, but his last trip didn't go well.
He left Pyongyang in July saying that progress had been made, but a few hours later North Korea denounced his "demands as those of a mafia man".
In a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea pledged to dismantle a missile site and a nuclear complex if the United States applied "appropriate measures".
He said Kim had communicated to him that the "corresponding measures" he was seeking were the security guarantees Trump had promised in Singapore and steps toward normalizing relations with Washington.
Harvard students give a course on how to get enough rest
Thanks to a new course being taught this year at Harvard University, all college students are getting more sleep in an attempt to combat the growing macho culture of studying all night and drinking caffeine.
One professor found that students at the world's top universities often have no idea about basic self-care.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School, and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital designed the course, believed to be the first of its kind in the United States.
His motivation to start the course came after giving a talk on how sleep deprivation affects learning.
At the end of the course, a girl came up to me and asked why she only found out about this now, in her senior year.
He said that no one had ever told him about the importance of sleep, which surprised me", she told The Telegraph.
The course, taught for the first time this year, explains to students the basics of how good sleep habits contribute to academic and athletic performance, as well as improving overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services, noted that the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students were barely sleeping during the week.
The one-hour course includes a number of interactive tasks.
In one section, there's a picture of a dorm room, where students click on coffee cups, curtains, sneakers and books that inform them about the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of sleep deprivation on athletic performance and the importance of establishing a bedtime routine.
In another section, participants are told how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
Afterwards, a campus icon with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routines.
We know it's not going to change student behavior instantly.
However, we believe they have a right to know, just as anyone has a right to know the health effects of smoking tobacco", added Professor Czeisler.
He said the culture of "pride of staying up all night" still exists and added that modern technology and the increasing pressure students are under meant that sleep deprivation was a growing problem.
Getting enough sleep and good quality sleep should be the students' "secret weapon" to combat stress, fatigue and anxiety; even to prevent weight gain, as sleep deprivation causes the brain to generate a feeling of hunger, so they want to eat all the time.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California student of chemical biology and physics, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after attending one of his classes the previous year during his first year at Harvard.
She noted that the course had opened her eyes and inspired her to expand it to the entire campus.
He hopes the next step will be to require all graduate students to complete a similar program of study before joining the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommends that students consider putting on an alarm to go to bed and another to wake up, and that they be aware of the harmful effects of the blue light emitted from the screens of electrical appliances and LEDs, which can alter circadian rhythms, so that they would eventually have trouble falling asleep.
