Almanac: The inventor of the Geiger counter
And now, a page from the Sunday Morning Almanac section: September 30, 1882, 136 years ago today, and counting... the future physicist Johannes Wilhelm Hans Geiger was born in Germany.
Geiger developed a method to detect and measure radioactivity, an invention that culminated in the device known as the Geiger counter.
The Geiger counter, which has been a mainstay of science ever since, also became a mainstay of pop culture, as in the 1950 film The Bells of Coronado, with actors Roy Rogers and Dale Evans in the seemingly incompatible roles of cowboy scientists:
Man: What the hell is that?
Rogers: It's a Geiger counter, it's used to locate radioactive minerals, like uranium.
When you put on your headphones, you can hear the effect of the waves emitted by the radioactivity of minerals.
Evans: It's like a radio!
Hans Geiger died in 1945, when he was about to turn 63.
But the invention that bears his name lives on.
A new cancer vaccine may teach the immune system to "see" malignant cells
A new cancer vaccine can teach the immune system to "see" malignant cells and kill them.
As part of the treatment, the vaccine teaches the immune system to recognize malignant cells.
The method requires extracting immune cells from a patient and altering them in the lab.
So they can "see" a protein common to many cancers and re-inject it.
A trial of the vaccine is generating promising results in patients with different cancers.
One woman treated with the vaccine, which teaches the immune system to recognize malignant cells, saw her ovarian cancer disappear for more than 18 months.
The method requires extracting immune cells from a patient and altering them in the lab so that they can "see" a protein common to many cancers, called HER2, and then re-inject the cells.
Professor Jay Berzofsky, of the U.S. National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, Maryland, commented: 'Our results suggest that we have a very promising vaccine.'
HER2 "promotes the growth of different types of cancer", such as breast, ovarian, lung and colorectal cancer, explained Professor Berzofsky.
A similar approach of taking immune cells from patients and 'training' them to attack cancer cells has worked in the treatment of a type of leukemia.
