In the country there are more than 820,000 people affected, according to the health authorities.
In the second quarter of 2018 alone, some 40 000 new cases were reported.
The vast majority of these were sexually transmitted, which is a change from the past.
Traditionally, HIV spread rapidly in parts of China as a result of transfusions of infected blood.
However, the number of people who contract HIV in this way has practically all decreased, Chinese health authorities said at a conference held in Yunnan Province.
Each year, the number of people living with HIV and AIDS in China increases by about 100,000 people.
Sexual transmission of HIV is a serious problem in China's LGBT community.
Homosexuality was decriminalized in China in 1997, but the LGBT community suffers a lot of discrimination.
Because of the country's conservative values, studies have estimated that between 70 percent and 90 percent of men who have sex with men will eventually marry women.
Many of the transmissions of diseases are due to not using adequate protection in these relationships.
Since 2003, the Chinese government has promised universal access to HIV medicines as part of an attempt to tackle the problem.
