It has now become a tradition to look for Brexit nods in any new film with a British focus. It seems that this is the appropriate thing to do with this new installment of the parody action-comedy franchise Johnny English, which began in 2003 with Johnny English and came back to life in 2011 with Johnny English Returns.
Is this ironic self-satire about how clearly insane we are the nation's new export opportunity?
In any case, the incompetent Johnny English, with his bulging eyes and expressionless face, has renewed his license to screw up for a second time, and his name alone hints that, more than anything, this is a comic creation designed for non-English-speaking cinematic territories.
Of course, it's the ridiculous secret agent who, despite his bizarre claims of lavish glamour, has a little Clouseau, a touch of Mr. Bean and a dash of that guy who played a single note on the Chariots of Fire theme that was played at the opening ceremony of the London 2012 Olympic Games.
In addition, it was originally based on the mysterious traveler and international man represented years ago by Atkinson in the now forgotten Barclaycard television ads, sowing chaos behind him.
In this latest installment, there are one or two good moments.
I loved watching Johnny English approach a helicopter in medieval armor as the propellers crashed into the hull.
Atkinson's gift for physical comedy is obvious, but the humor is rather short-lived and strangely superfluous, especially now that "serious" movie franchises like 007 and Mission: Impossible add comic ingredients seamlessly.
The humor seems more directed at children than adults, and to me, Johnny English's absurd misadventures are not as witty and apt as Atkinson's silent jokes in the role of Mr. Bean.
Now, the repeated argument of the day is that Britain is in serious trouble.
A hacker has infiltrated Britain's top-secret spy network, revealing the identities of all its active agents to the dismay of the agent in charge, a pitifully small role for Kevin Eldon.
