His intelligence advisors inform him that, since all active spies are in danger, he will have to resort to one who is retired.
That's got to be the clumsy Johnny English, who now teaches at a seedy school, although he gives off-the-record lessons on how to be a secret agent: there are some good jokes, since this is a spy academy like the School of Rock.
English is flown to Whitehall for an emergency meeting and reunites with his long-suffering old sidekick Bough, again represented by Ben Miller.
Now, Bough is a man married to a submarine captain, a nice role for which Vicki Pepperdine is not sufficiently tapped.
So, the Batman and Robin who do things terribly wrong in Her Majesty's Secret Service are back in action, with the beautiful female fatality Ophelia Bulletova, played by Olga Kurylenko.
Meanwhile, the Prime Minister is falling into the dangerous clutches of a charismatic tech billionaire who claims he can solve Britain's IT problems: the sinister Jason Volta, played by Jake Lacy.
English and Bough begin their odyssey of absurd situations: they disguise themselves as waiters, set fire to an elegant French restaurant, unleash chaos by hiding in Volta's luxurious yacht; moreover, English becomes pure anarchy when he attempts to use a virtual reality headset to familiarize himself with the interior of Volta's house.
They were definitely used to the full in that last sequence, but as funny and as loud as it is, the whole thing still has a somewhat childish feel to it.
A fairly regular product.
As with the other Johnny English films, I couldn't help but wonder if the British film industry couldn't give Rowan Atkinson a role that would do true justice to her talent.
