The inventor of the World Wide Web is planning to start a new Internet to compete with Google and Facebook
Tim Berners-Lee, the inventor of the World Wide Web, is launching a new company that is trying to rival Facebook, Amazon and Google.
Inrupt is the latest project from the tech legend, a company that builds on Berners-Lee's open-source Solid platform.
Solid allows users to choose where to store their data and which people will have access to what information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that the intention behind Inrupt is to "take over the world".
"It has to be now", he said about the startup.
"This is a historic moment".
The application uses Solid's technology so that users can create their own "personal data online store" or a POD.
It can contain lists, to-do lists, calendar, music library, and other personal and professional tools.
It's as if Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify are all available in one browser and at the same time.
One thing that is unique about personal online data storage is that the user is the one who completely decides who can access what kind of information.
The company calls it "personal empowerment through data".
The idea of Inrupt, according to the company's CEO, John Bruce, is to incorporate the resources, processes and skills necessary for Solid to reach everyone.
At the moment, the company consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform that IBM bought, some of the on-staff developers who were hired to work on the project, and a community of volunteer programmers.
Starting this week, technology developers around the world will be able to create their own decentralized apps with the tools available on Inrupt's website.
Berners-Lee said that he and his team are not talking to "Facebook and Google about whether or not to introduce a radical change where all their business models are completely modified overnight.
"We're not going to ask permission".
In a Medium post on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote of Inrupt that "its mission is to provide commercial power and an ecosystem to help protect the integrity and quality of the new web created in Solid".
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet when he founded the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has played a very influential role in the debate on net neutrality.
Despite even being launching Inrupt, Berners-Lee will remain the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
