Bernard Vann - the clergyman who won a Victory Cross in World War I
The only Church of England cleric to win a Victoria Cross during World War I as a combatant has been honoured in his home town 100 years later.
Lieutenant Colonel Reverend Bernard Vann was awarded the VC on 29 September 1918 in the attack on Bellenglise and Lehaucourt.
However, he was killed by a sniper four days later and never knew that he had been awarded Britain's highest military honor.
On Saturday, his two grandchildren unveiled a memorial stone at a parade in Rushden, Northamptonshire.
One of them, Michael Vann, said that it was "of special symbolism" that the stone was discovered exactly 100 years after the battle that earned his grandfather the decoration.
According to the London Gazette, on September 29, 1918, Lieutenant Colonel Vann led his battalion through the Saint-Quentin Canal "through thick fog and under heavy machine-gun and cannon fire".
He then ran to the line of fire and, with "greatest courage", advanced the line before reaching a cannon with one hand and shooting down three of the detachment.
Lieutenant Colonel Vann was killed by a German sniper on October 4, 1918, just one month after the war ended.
Michael Vann, 72, said that his grandfather's actions were "so great that I could never measure up to him, but they were very instructive".
He and his brother, Dr. James Vann, also laid a wreath after the parade, which featured the Brentwood Imperial Youth Band.
Michael Vann said that "it was a privilege for him to be part of the parade" and added that "the courage of a true hero is evident when he is shown such a large support".
