The new German warship, postponed again
The German Navy's new frigate should have been commissioned in 2014 to replace the old ships from the Cold War era, but it won't be until at least next year due to faulty systems and rising costs, local media reported.
The delivery of the "Rheinland-Pfalz", the lead ship of the new Baden-Württemberg class frigates, has now been postponed until the first half of 2019, according to a military spokesman quoted by the newspaper Die Zeit.
The ship was supposed to have joined the Navy in 2014, but problems that arose after delivery derailed the completion of the ambitious project.
The four Baden-Wuerttemberg-class ships requested by the Navy in 2007 will replace the aging Bremen-class frigates.
We know they will include a powerful cannon, an array of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles, as well as some stealth technologies, such as radar, infrared and very low acoustic signals.
Other important features include longer maintenance periods, so that they can be deployed for up to two years away from the ports of origin.
However, the continuing delays have meant that the innovative ships - which were supposed to allow Germany to project its power overseas - will be outdated by the time they enter service, notes Die Zeit.
The ill-fated F125 frigate made headlines last year, when the German Navy officially refused to put the ship into service and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
It was the first time the Navy had returned a ship to a shipyard after its delivery.
Little was known of the reasons behind the return, but German media cited a number of crucial "software and hardware defects" that left the ship virtually useless if sent on a combat mission.
The software deficiencies were particularly important, as the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class ships will be operated by a crew of about 120 sailors - half the personnel of the former Bremen-class frigates.
The vessel was also found to be overweight, which reduces its performance and limits the Navy's ability to add future upgrades.
The 7,000-tonne "Rheinland-Pfalz" is believed to be twice as heavy as other ships of a similar class used by the Germans in World War II.
In addition to the faulty hardware, the cost of the entire project, including the training of the crew, has also been a problem.
It is believed to have reached €3.1 billion ($3.6 billion), instead of the initial €2.2 billion.
The problems attributed to the new frigates are of particular relevance in the light of recent warnings about the reduction of Germany's naval power.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the German parliament's defense committee, acknowledged that the Navy is "running out of ships capable of deployment".
The officer said the problem has worsened over time, because the old ships were decommissioned but not replaced with new ones.
He regretted that none of the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class frigates had been able to join the Navy.
The National Trust spies on the secret lives of bats
This new research, which has been carried out in a state in the Scottish Highlands, tries to discover how bats use the landscape in their search for food.
It is hoped that all that is learned will shed more light on the behavior of the only flying mammals and help guide future conservation activities.
The study, carried out by the National Trust for Scotland, will follow common and soprano bats as well as Daubenton's river bats and long-eared browns from Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed at strategic locations on the property to track bat activities during the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also carry out mobile surveys with portable detectors.
Experts will analyze the sounds collected from the recordings to find out how often the bats call and which species do.
A report and a habitat map will then be produced to create a detailed picture of the environment and its behaviour.
Rob Dewar, a nature conservation adviser for NTS, hopes the results will reveal which areas of habitat are most important to bats and how each species uses them.
This information will determine the benefits of habitat management work such as the creation of grasslands and how forests should be maintained for bats and other associated species.
Bat populations in Scotland and the United Kingdom have declined considerably over the last century.
They are under threat from construction and development affecting their nests and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and electrical wiring can also pose a risk to them, as can insecticide papers and other chemical treatments of building materials or attacks by domestic cats.
Bats aren't really blind,
But because of their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes in getting their target.
They use a sophisticated echolocation technique that locates ants and obstacles in their flight path.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of over 270 historic buildings, 38 major gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes the issue of bats very seriously.
It has ten trained experts who regularly conduct surveys, nest inspections, and occasionally rescues.
The organisation has even opened Scotland's first and only dedicated bat reserve in the Threave area of Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
The property manager, David Thompson, says it's the ideal territory for them.
"Here in Threave, we have a fantastic area for bats", he said.
"We have old buildings, many old trees and all the right habitat.
However, there is still a lot that is unknown about bats, so the work we are doing here and on other properties will help us better understand what they need to thrive".
It emphasises the importance of checking for bats before carrying out maintenance work on the property, as a breeding colony can be destroyed involuntarily and 400 females and young may be killed, which would wipe out an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, harass or disturb them, as well as destroy their colonies.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish officer in charge of the Bat Conservation Trust, has encouraged the public to help.
He said: "We still have a lot to learn about bats and many other species about which we don't know how their populations evolve".
